choices.text:
by bicycle.This means that for part of the distance, I still walk, in large part because I don’t have a sturdy enough bike to take on cobblestone streets. The other thing that is a struggle is the fact that occasionally, we get some rain. I wish I was making this up, but I’m not. Of course, I have an umbrella. It folds up in a nice purple protective case. It’s extremely long, so it’s easy to hold and leaves plenty of leeway so you don’t look like an idiot. But again, in Belgium, they speak a language that is named after the country, and in that country, they use euros. There is only one Uber. It’s basically like AAA, but the difference is you have to call it, it can take hours to show up, and you might not get to your destination by the time you need to be there. There is no Driver. There is no good alternative, because busses, which are typically how those who lack a bike get around their destinations, don’t take us to where we need to go. So, I decided that Monday’s outing should be on the part of the tram line that runs close to the trucks on Thor de God, or Thor of the Covenant, because that’s the only way to get close to me.

Alright. Monday was tough for a couple of reasons. 1. Sometimes, finding out what the buses available now through fall will cost you is tricky enough
